+# Chroma Rust Workspace
+
+This workspace contains the modular Rust codebase for Chroma, organized into separate library crates for better maintainability, testing, and benchmarking.
+
+## Workspace Structure
+
+### Library Crates
+
+- **chroma-proto** - Protocol buffer definitions and generated code
+  - Contains all protobuf definitions for the Chroma API
+  - Provides type-safe bindings for gRPC communication
+
+- **chroma-types** - Core domain types and data structures
+  - Collections, segments, records, and metadata types
+  - Operations and flush types
+  - Error definitions
+  - No external service dependencies
+
+- **chroma-distance** - Distance metric implementations
+  - Euclidean, Cosine, and Inner Product distance functions
+  - SIMD-optimized implementations (SSE, AVX, NEON)
+  - Standalone benchmarks for distance calculations
+  - Location: `rust/chroma-distance/benches/`
+
+- **chroma-blockstore** - Block storage abstractions and implementations
+  - Arrow-based block storage
+  - Memory-backed block storage
+  - Sparse index implementations
+  - Standalone benchmarks available
+  - Location: `rust/chroma-blockstore/benches/`
+
+- **chroma-system** - Actor system and execution framework
+  - Component lifecycle management
+  - Message passing infrastructure
+  - Executor and scheduler implementations
+
+- **chroma-index** - Indexing implementations
+  - HNSW (Hierarchical Navigable Small World) index
+  - Full-text search with Tantivy
+  - Metadata filtering
+  - Note: Requires hnswlib C++ library (see Dependencies below)
+
+### Application Crate
+
+- **worker** - Main application binary
+  - Query service
+  - Compaction service
+  - Integrates all library crates
+  - Location: `rust/worker/`
+
+## Building the Workspace
+
+```bash
+# Build all crates
+cargo build --workspace
+
+# Build specific crate
+cargo build -p chroma-distance
+
+# Run tests
+cargo test --workspace
+
+# Check compilation without building
+cargo check --workspace
+```
+
+## Running Benchmarks
+
+Each library crate with benchmarks can be benchmarked individually:
+
+```bash
+# Benchmark distance metrics
+cargo bench -p chroma-distance
+
+# Benchmark blockstore operations
+cargo bench -p chroma-blockstore
+```
+
+## Dependencies
+
+### External C++ Dependencies
+
+The `chroma-index` crate requires the hnswlib library to be available:
+
+```bash
+# The hnswlib library should be located at ../../../hnswlib/
+# relative to the rust directory structure
+```
+
+## Dependency Graph
+
+```
+worker
+├── chroma-proto
+├── chroma-types (depends on chroma-proto)
+├── chroma-distance
+├── chroma-blockstore (depends on chroma-types)
+├── chroma-system (depends on chroma-types)
+└── chroma-index (depends on chroma-types, chroma-blockstore, chroma-distance)
+```
+
+## Benefits of Modular Structure
+
+1. **Clear Dependency Boundaries** - Each crate explicitly declares its dependencies, making the architecture more maintainable
+
+2. **Independent Testing** - Library crates can be tested in isolation without pulling in unnecessary dependencies
+
+3. **Focused Benchmarking** - Each crate can have its own benchmarks, making performance testing more targeted
+
+4. **Parallel Compilation** - Cargo can compile independent crates in parallel, improving build times
+
+5. **Reusability** - Library crates can be reused in other projects or services
+
+6. **Smaller Build Artifacts** - Applications only include the crates they need
+
+## Development Workflow
+
+### Adding a New Feature
+
+1. Identify which crate the feature belongs to
+2. Implement in the appropriate library crate
+3. Add tests in the same crate
+4. Add benchmarks if performance-critical
+5. Update the worker crate to use the new feature
+
+### Running Services
+
+```bash
+# Query service
+cargo run --bin query_service
+
+# Compaction service
+cargo run --bin compaction_service
+```
+
+## Testing Strategy
+
+```bash
+# Unit tests for specific crate
+cargo test -p chroma-types
+
+# Integration tests
+cargo test -p worker
+
+# All tests
+cargo test --workspace
+```
